 cells","Chief cells"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe stomach contains \u003Cstrong\u003EG cells\u003C/strong\u003E produce gastrin, which stimulates acid secretion, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eparietal cells\u003C/strong\u003E which secrete hydrochloric acid and intrinsic factor. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChief cells\u003C/strong\u003E produce pepsinogen and are found in the mucosal layer of the fundus and body of the stomach. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ED cells\u003C/strong\u003E are found in the pyloric antrum, the duodenum and the pancreatic islets. They produce somatostatin, which acts as an inhibitory hormone that reduces gastric acid secretion and inhibits the release of multiple gastrointestinal hormones. \u003Cstrong\u003EI cells\u003C/strong\u003E are found mainly in the duodenum and produce cholecystokinin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Somatostatin is produced by D cells in the gastrointestinal tract and pancreatic islets.","Somatostatin inhibits the secretion of multiple gastrointestinal hormones and reduces gastric acid secretion."],"references":["Johnson, L. R. (2018). Gastrointestinal Physiology E-Book: Gastrointestinal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","O\u0027Toole TJ, Sharma S. Physiology, Somatostatin. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538327/","Arnold R, H\u00fclst MV, Neuhof CH, Schwarting H, Becker HD, Creutzfeldt W. Antral gastrin-producing G-cells and somatostatin-producing D-cells in different states of gastric acid secretion. Gut. 1982 Apr;23(4):285-91. doi: 10.1136/gut.23.4.285. PMID: 6122629; PMCID: PMC1419730.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRev